file between two .RC files","pos":[1472,1534]},{"content":"How do you divide project resources into multiple .RC files","pos":[1544,1603]},{"content":"How do you (and the tools) manage build dependencies between .RC, .CPP, and .H files","pos":[1613,1697]},{"content":"You should be aware that if you add an additional resource file to your project, ClassWizard will not recognize the resources in the added file.","pos":[1704,1848]},{"content":"This note is structured to answer the above questions as follows:","pos":[1855,1920]},{"pos":[1928,2149],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Overview of How Visual C++ Manages Resource Files and Header Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> provides an overview of how the Resource Set Includes command in Visual C++ lets you use multiple resource files and header files in the same project.","source":"**Overview of How Visual C++ Manages Resource Files and Header Files** provides an overview of how the Resource Set Includes command in Visual C++ lets you use multiple resource files and header files in the same project."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Analysis of AppWizard-created .RC and .H Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> looks at the multiple resource and header files that are used by an AppWizard-created application.","pos":[2157,2306],"source":"**Analysis of AppWizard-created .RC and .H Files** looks at the multiple resource and header files that are used by an AppWizard-created application."},{"content":"These files serve as a good model for additional resource files and header files you might want to add to your project.","pos":[2307,2426]},{"pos":[2434,2571],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Including Additional Header Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> describes where you might want to include multiple header files, and provides details how to do so.","source":"**Including Additional Header Files** describes where you might want to include multiple header files, and provides details how to do so."},{"pos":[2579,2748],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Sharing a Header File Between Two .RC Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> shows how you can share one header file between multiple .RC files in different projects, or perhaps in the same project.","source":"**Sharing a Header File Between Two .RC Files** shows how you can share one header file between multiple .RC files in different projects, or perhaps in the same project."},{"pos":[2756,2925],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Using Multiple Resource Files in the Same Project<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> describes where you might want to break up your project into multiple .RC files, and provides details how to do so.","source":"**Using Multiple Resource Files in the Same Project** describes where you might want to break up your project into multiple .RC files, and provides details how to do so."},{"pos":[2933,3086],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enforcement of Non-Editable Visual C++ Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> describes how you can make sure Visual C++ does not edit and unintentionally reformat a custom resource.","source":"**Enforcement of Non-Editable Visual C++ Files** describes how you can make sure Visual C++ does not edit and unintentionally reformat a custom resource."},{"pos":[3094,3283],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Managing Symbols Shared by Multiple Visual C++-Edited .RC Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> describes how to share the same symbols across multiple .RC files and how to avoid assigning duplicate ID numeric values.","source":"**Managing Symbols Shared by Multiple Visual C++-Edited .RC Files** describes how to share the same symbols across multiple .RC files and how to avoid assigning duplicate ID numeric values."},{"pos":[3291,3460],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Managing Dependencies Between .RC, .CPP, and .H Files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> describes how Visual C++ avoids unnecessary recompiling .CPP files that are dependent on resource symbol files.","source":"**Managing Dependencies Between .RC, .CPP, and .H Files** describes how Visual C++ avoids unnecessary recompiling .CPP files that are dependent on resource symbol files."},{"pos":[3468,3672],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>How Visual C++ Manages Set Includes Information<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> provides technical details about how Visual C++ keeps track of multiple (nested) .RC files and multiple header files that are #include'd by an .RC file.","source":"**How Visual C++ Manages Set Includes Information** provides technical details about how Visual C++ keeps track of multiple (nested) .RC files and multiple header files that are #include'd by an .RC file."},{"content":"Overview of How Visual C++ Manages Resource Files and Header Files","pos":[3681,3747]},{"content":"Visual C++ manages a single .RC resource file and a corresponding .H header file as a tightly coupled pair of files.","pos":[3756,3872]},{"content":"When you edit and save resources in an .RC file, you indirectly edit and save symbols in the corresponding .H file.","pos":[3873,3988]},{"content":"Although you can open and edit multiple .RC files at a time (using Visual C++'s MDI user interface) for any given .RC file you indirectly edit exactly one corresponding header file.","pos":[3989,4170]},{"content":"Symbol Header File","pos":[4179,4197]},{"content":"By default, Visual C++ always names the corresponding header file RESOURCE.H, regardless of the name of the resource file (e.g., MYAPP.RC).","pos":[4206,4345]},{"content":"Using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource Includes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command from the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>View<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> menu in Visual C++, you can change the name of this header file by updating the Symbol Header File file in the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Set Includes<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> dialog box.","pos":[4346,4543],"source":" Using the **Resource Includes** command from the **View** menu in Visual C++, you can change the name of this header file by updating the Symbol Header File file in the **Set Includes** dialog box."},{"content":"Read-Only Symbol Directives","pos":[4552,4579]},{"content":"Although Visual C++ only edits one header file for any given .RC file, Visual C++ supports references to symbols defined in additional read-only header files.","pos":[4588,4746]},{"content":"Using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource Includes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command from the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>View<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> menu in Visual C++, you can specify any number of additional read-only header files as Read-Only Symbol Directives.","pos":[4747,4920],"source":" Using the **Resource Includes** command from the **View** menu in Visual C++, you can specify any number of additional read-only header files as Read-Only Symbol Directives."},{"content":"The \"read-only\" restriction means that when you add a new resource in the .RC file, you can use a symbol defined in the read-only header file; but if you delete the resource, the symbol still remains defined in the read-only header file.","pos":[4921,5158]},{"content":"You cannot change the numeric value assigned to a read-only symbol.","pos":[5159,5226]},{"content":"Compile-Time Directives","pos":[5235,5258]},{"content":"Visual C++ also supports nesting of resource files, where one .RC file is #include'd within another.","pos":[5267,5367]},{"content":"When you edit a given .RC file using Visual C++, any resources in the #include'd files are not visible.","pos":[5368,5471]},{"content":"But when you compile the .RC file, the #include'd files are also compiled.","pos":[5472,5546]},{"content":"Using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource Includes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command from the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>View<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> menu in Visual C++, you can specify any number of #include'd .RC files as Compile-Time Directives.","pos":[5547,5703],"source":" Using the **Resource Includes** command from the **View** menu in Visual C++, you can specify any number of #include'd .RC files as Compile-Time Directives."},{"content":"Note what happens if you read into Visual C++ an .RC file that #include's another .RC file that is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>not<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> specified as a Compile-Time Directive.","pos":[5710,5853],"source":"Note what happens if you read into Visual C++ an .RC file that #include's another .RC file that is *not* specified as a Compile-Time Directive."},{"content":"This situation might arise when you bring to Visual C++ an .RC file that you had been previously maintaining manually with a text editor.","pos":[5854,5991]},{"content":"When Visual C++ reads the #include'd .RC file, it merges the #include'd resources into the parent .RC file.","pos":[5992,6099]},{"content":"When you save the parent .RC file, the #include statement, in effect, will be replaced by the #include'd resources.","pos":[6100,6215]},{"content":"If you do not want this merge to happen, you should remove the #include statement from the parent .RC file <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>prior<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> to reading it into Visual C++; then using Visual C++, add back the same #include statement as a Compile-Time Directive.","pos":[6216,6450],"source":" If you do not want this merge to happen, you should remove the #include statement from the parent .RC file *prior* to reading it into Visual C++; then using Visual C++, add back the same #include statement as a Compile-Time Directive."},{"content":"Visual C++ saves in an .RC file the three kinds of above Set Includes information (Symbol Header File, Read-Only Symbol Directives, and Compile-Time Directives) in #include directives <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>and<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in TEXTINCLUDE resources.","pos":[6457,6672],"source":"Visual C++ saves in an .RC file the three kinds of above Set Includes information (Symbol Header File, Read-Only Symbol Directives, and Compile-Time Directives) in #include directives *and* in TEXTINCLUDE resources."},{"content":"The TEXTINCLUDE resources, an implementation detail that you do not normally need to deal with, are explained in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How Visual C++ Manages Set Includes Information<ept id=\"p1\">](#_mfcnotes_tn035_set_includes)</ept>.","pos":[6673,6867],"source":" The TEXTINCLUDE resources, an implementation detail that you do not normally need to deal with, are explained in [How Visual C++ Manages Set Includes Information](#_mfcnotes_tn035_set_includes)."},{"content":"Analysis of AppWizard-Created .RC and .H Files","pos":[6876,6922]},{"content":"Examining the application code produced by AppWizard provides insight into how Visual C++ manages multiple resource files and header files.","pos":[6931,7070]},{"content":"The code excerpts examined below are from a MYAPP application produced by AppWizard using the default options.","pos":[7071,7181]},{"content":"An AppWizard-created application uses multiple resource files and multiple header files, as summarized in the diagram below:","pos":[7188,7312]},{"content":"You can view these multiple file relationships using the Visual C++ File/Set Includes command.","pos":[7491,7585]},{"content":"MYAPP.RC","pos":[7592,7600]},{"content":"The application resource file that you edit using Visual C++.","pos":[7604,7665]},{"content":"RESOURCE.H is the application-specific header file.","pos":[7672,7723]},{"content":"It is always named RESOURCE.H by AppWizard, consistent with Visual C++'s default naming of the header file.","pos":[7724,7831]},{"content":"The #include for this header file is the first statement in the resource file (MYAPP.RC):","pos":[7832,7921]},{"content":"RES\\MYAPP.RC2","pos":[8023,8036]},{"content":"Contains resources that will not be edited by Visual C++ but will be included in the final compiled .EXE file.","pos":[8040,8150]},{"content":"AppWizard creates no such resources by default, since Visual C++ can edit all of the standard resources, including the version resource (a new feature in this release).","pos":[8151,8319]},{"content":"An empty file is generated by AppWizard in case you wish to add your own custom formatted resources to this file.","pos":[8320,8433]},{"content":"If you use custom formatted resources, you can add them to RES\\MYAPP.RC2 and edit them using the Visual C++ text editor.","pos":[8440,8560]},{"content":"AFXRES.RC and AFXPRINT.RC contain standard resources required by certain features of the framework.","pos":[8567,8666]},{"content":"Like RES\\MYAPP.RC2, these two framework-provided resource files are #include'd at the end of MYAPP.RC, and they are specified in the Compile-Time Directives of the Set Includes dialog box.","pos":[8667,8855]},{"content":"Thus, you do not directly view or edit these framework resources while you edit MYAPP.RC in Visual C++, but they are compiled into the application's binary .RES file and final .EXE file.","pos":[8856,9042]},{"content":"For more information on the standard framework resources, including procedures for modifying them, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Technical Note 23<ept id=\"p1\">](../mfc/tn023-standard-mfc-resources.md)</ept>.","pos":[9043,9206],"source":" For more information on the standard framework resources, including procedures for modifying them, see [Technical Note 23](../mfc/tn023-standard-mfc-resources.md)."},{"content":"AFXRES.H defines standard symbols, such as <ph id=\"ph1\">`ID_FILE_NEW`</ph>, used by the framework and specifically used in AFXRES.RC.","pos":[9213,9328],"source":"AFXRES.H defines standard symbols, such as `ID_FILE_NEW`, used by the framework and specifically used in AFXRES.RC."},{"content":"AFXRES.H also #include's WINRES.H, which contains a subset of WINDOWS.H that are needed by Visual C++ generated .RC files as well as AFXRES.RC.","pos":[9329,9472]},{"content":"The symbols defined in AFXRES.H are available as you edit the application resource file (MYAPP.RC).","pos":[9473,9572]},{"content":"For example, <ph id=\"ph1\">`ID_FILE_NEW`</ph> is used for the File New menu item in MYAPP.RC's menu resource.","pos":[9573,9663],"source":" For example, `ID_FILE_NEW` is used for the File New menu item in MYAPP.RC's menu resource."},{"content":"You cannot change or delete these framework-defined symbols.","pos":[9664,9724]},{"pos":[9774,9807],"content":"Including Additional Header Files"},{"content":"The AppWizard-created application includes only two header files: RESOURCE.H and AFXRES.H.","pos":[9814,9904]},{"content":"Only RESOURCE.H is application-specific.","pos":[9905,9945]},{"content":"You may need to include additional read-only header files in the following cases:","pos":[9946,10027]},{"content":"The header file is provided by an external source, or you want to share the header file among multiple projects or multiple parts of the same project.","pos":[10034,10184]},{"content":"The header file has formatting and comments that you do not want Visual C++ to change or filter out when it saves the file.","pos":[10191,10314]},{"content":"For example, maybe you want to preserve #define's that use symbolic arithmetic such as:","pos":[10315,10402]},{"pos":[10656,10829],"content":"You can include additional read-only header files by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource Includes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command to specify the #include statement as a second Read-Only Symbol Directive, as in:","source":"You can include additional read-only header files by using the **Resource Includes** command to specify the #include statement as a second Read-Only Symbol Directive, as in:"},{"content":"The new file relationship diagram now looks like this:","pos":[10895,10949]},{"content":"Sharing a Header File Between Two .RC Files","pos":[11144,11187]},{"content":"You may want to share a header file between two .RC files that are in different projects, or possibly the same project.","pos":[11196,11315]},{"content":"To do so, simply apply the Read-Only Directives technique described above to both .RC files.","pos":[11316,11408]},{"content":"In the case where the two .RC files are for different applications (different projects), the result is illustrated in the following diagram:","pos":[11409,11549]},{"content":"The case where the second header file is shared by two .RC files in the same application (project) is discussed below.","pos":[11905,12023]},{"content":"Using Multiple Resource Files in the Same Project","pos":[12032,12081]},{"content":"Visual C++ and the Resource Compiler support multiple .RC files in the same project through #include's of one .RC file within another.","pos":[12090,12224]},{"content":"Multiple nesting is allowed.","pos":[12225,12253]},{"content":"There are various reasons to split your project's resources into multiple .RC files:","pos":[12254,12338]},{"content":"It is easier to manage a large number of resources among multiple project team members if you split the resources into multiple .RC files.","pos":[12348,12486]},{"content":"If you use a source control management package for checking out files and checking in changes, splitting the resources into multiple .RC files will give you finer control over managing changes to resources.","pos":[12487,12693]},{"content":"If you want to use preprocessor directives, such as #ifdef, #endif, and #define, for portions of your resources, you must isolate them in read-only resources that will be compiled by the Resource Compiler.","pos":[12703,12908]},{"content":"Component .RC files will load and save faster in Visual C++ than one composite .RC file.","pos":[12918,13006]},{"content":"If you want to maintain a resource with a text editor in a human-readable form, you should keep it in a .RC file separate from the one Visual C++ edits.","pos":[13016,13168]},{"content":"If you need to keep a user-defined resource in a binary or text form that is interpretable by another specialized data editor, then you should keep it in a separate .RC file so Visual C++ does not change the format to hexadecimal data.","pos":[13178,13413]},{"content":"The .WAV (sound) file resources in the MFC Advanced Concepts sample <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>SPEAKN<ept id=\"p1\">](../visual-cpp-samples.md)</ept> are a good example.","pos":[13414,13536],"source":" The .WAV (sound) file resources in the MFC Advanced Concepts sample [SPEAKN](../visual-cpp-samples.md) are a good example."},{"content":"You can #include a SECOND.RC in the Compile-Time Directives in the Set Includes dialog box:","pos":[13543,13634]},{"content":"The result is illustrated in the following diagram:","pos":[13878,13929]},{"content":"Using Compile-Time Directives, you can organize your Visual C++-editable and non-editable resources into multiple .RC files, where the \"master\" MYAPP.RC does nothing but #include the other .RC files.","pos":[14123,14322]},{"content":"If you are using a Visual C++ project .MAK file, then you should include the \"master\" .RC file in the project so that all the #include'd resources are compiled with your application.","pos":[14323,14505]},{"content":"Enforcement of Noneditable Visual C++ Files","pos":[14514,14557]},{"content":"The AppWizard-created RES\\MYAPP.RC2 file is an example of a file that contains resources that you do <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>not<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> want to accidentally read into Visual C++ and then write it back out with loss of formatting information.","pos":[14566,14778],"source":"The AppWizard-created RES\\MYAPP.RC2 file is an example of a file that contains resources that you do *not* want to accidentally read into Visual C++ and then write it back out with loss of formatting information."},{"content":"To protect against this, place the following lines in the beginning of the RES\\MYAPP.RC2 file:","pos":[14779,14873]},{"content":"When Visual C++ compiles the .RC file, it defines <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>APSTUDIO_INVOKED<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> as well as <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>RC_INVOKED<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[14999,15096],"source":"When Visual C++ compiles the .RC file, it defines **APSTUDIO_INVOKED** as well as **RC_INVOKED**."},{"content":"If the AppWizard-created file structure is corrupted and Visual C++ reads the #error line above, it reports a fatal error and abort the reading of the .RC file.","pos":[15097,15257]},{"content":"Managing Symbols Shared by Multiple Visual C++-Edited .RC Files","pos":[15266,15329]},{"content":"Two issues arise when you split up your resources into multiple .RC files that you want to edit separately in Visual C++:","pos":[15338,15459]},{"content":"You might want to share the same symbols across multiple .RC files.","pos":[15469,15536]},{"content":"You need to help Visual C++ avoid assigning the same ID numeric values to distinct resources (symbols).","pos":[15546,15649]},{"content":"The following diagram illustrates an organization of .RC and .H files that deals with the first issue:","pos":[15656,15758]},{"content":"In this example, string resources are kept in one resource file, MYSTRS.RC, and menus are kept in another, MYMENUS.RC.","pos":[15952,16070]},{"content":"Some symbols, such as for commands, may need to be shared between the two files.","pos":[16071,16151]},{"content":"For example, a ID_TOOLS_SPELL may be the menu command ID for the Spell item in a Tools menu; and it may also be the string ID of the command prompt displayed by the framework in the application's main window status bar.","pos":[16152,16371]},{"content":"The ID_TOOLS_SPELL symbol is kept in the shared header file, MYSHARED.H.","pos":[16378,16450]},{"content":"You maintain this shared header file manually with a text editor; Visual C++ does not directly edit it.","pos":[16451,16554]},{"content":"In the two resource files MYSTRS.RC and MYMENUS.RC, you specify #include MYSHARED.H in the Read-Only Directives for MYAPP.RC, using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resource Includes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command, as described earlier.","pos":[16555,16743],"source":" In the two resource files MYSTRS.RC and MYMENUS.RC, you specify #include MYSHARED.H in the Read-Only Directives for MYAPP.RC, using the **Resource Includes** command, as described earlier."},{"content":"It is most convenient to anticipate a symbol you will share before you attempt use it to identify any resource.","pos":[16750,16861]},{"content":"Add the symbol to the shared header file and, if you have not already #include'd the shared header file in the Read-Only Directives for the .RC file, do so before using the symbol.","pos":[16862,17042]},{"content":"If you did not anticipate sharing the symbol in this way, then you will have to manually (using a text editor) move the #define statement for the symbol from, say, MYMENUS.H to MYSHARED.H before using it in MYSTRS.RC.","pos":[17043,17260]},{"content":"When you manage symbols in multiple .RC files, you also must help Visual C++ avoid assigning the same ID numeric values to distinct resources (symbols).","pos":[17267,17419]},{"content":"For any given .RC file, Visual C++ incrementally assigns IDs in each of four ID domains.","pos":[17420,17508]},{"content":"Between editing sessions, Visual C++ keeps track of the last ID it assigned in each of the domains in the symbol header file for the .RC file.","pos":[17509,17651]},{"content":"Here is what the APS_NEXT values are for an empty (new) .RC file:","pos":[17652,17717]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT_RESOURCE_VALUE<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is the next symbol value that will be used for a dialog resource, menu resource, and so on.","pos":[17902,18022],"source":"**_APS_NEXT_RESOURCE_VALUE** is the next symbol value that will be used for a dialog resource, menu resource, and so on."},{"content":"The valid range for resource symbol values is 1 to 0x6FFF.","pos":[18023,18081]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT_COMMAND_VALUE<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is the next symbol value that will be used for a command identification.","pos":[18088,18188],"source":"**_APS_NEXT_COMMAND_VALUE** is the next symbol value that will be used for a command identification."},{"content":"The valid range for command symbol values is 0x8000 to 0xDFFF.","pos":[18189,18251]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT_CONTROL_VALUE<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is the next symbol value that will be used for a dialog control.","pos":[18258,18350],"source":"**_APS_NEXT_CONTROL_VALUE** is the next symbol value that will be used for a dialog control."},{"content":"The valid range for dialog control symbol values is 8 to 0xDFFF.","pos":[18351,18415]},{"pos":[18422,18577],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT_SYMED_VALUE<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is the next symbol value that will be issued when you manually assign a symbol value using the New command in the Symbol Browser.","source":"**_APS_NEXT_SYMED_VALUE** is the next symbol value that will be issued when you manually assign a symbol value using the New command in the Symbol Browser."},{"content":"Visual C++ starts with slightly higher values that the lowest legal value when creating a new .RC file.","pos":[18584,18687]},{"content":"AppWizard will also initialize these values to something more appropriate for MFC applications.","pos":[18688,18783]},{"content":"For more information about ID value ranges, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Technical Note 20<ept id=\"p1\">](../mfc/tn020-id-naming-and-numbering-conventions.md)</ept>.","pos":[18784,18905],"source":" For more information about ID value ranges, see [Technical Note 20](../mfc/tn020-id-naming-and-numbering-conventions.md)."},{"content":"Now every time you create a new resource file, even in the same project, Visual C++ defines the same <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph><ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> values.","pos":[18912,19036],"source":"Now every time you create a new resource file, even in the same project, Visual C++ defines the same **_APS_NEXT\\_** values."},{"content":"This means that if you add, say, multiple dialogs in two different .RC files, it is highly likely that the same #define value will be assigned to different dialogs.","pos":[19037,19201]},{"content":"For example, IDD_MY_DLG1 in the first .RC file might be assigned the same number, 101, as IDD_MY_DLG2 in a second .RC file.","pos":[19202,19325]},{"content":"To avoid this, you should reserve a separate numeric range for each of the four domains of IDs in the respective .RC files.","pos":[19332,19455]},{"content":"Do this by manually updating the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> values in each of the .RC files <ph id=\"ph1\">`before`</ph> you start adding resources.","pos":[19456,19571],"source":" Do this by manually updating the **_APS_NEXT** values in each of the .RC files `before` you start adding resources."},{"content":"For example, if the first .RC file uses the default <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> values, then you might want to assign the following <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>_APS_NEXT<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> values to the second .RC file:","pos":[19572,19734],"source":" For example, if the first .RC file uses the default **_APS_NEXT** values, then you might want to assign the following **_APS_NEXT** values to the second .RC file:"},{"content":"Of course, it is still possible that Visual C++ will assign so many IDs in the first .RC file that the numeric values start to overlap those reserved for the second .RC file.","pos":[19921,20095]},{"content":"You should reserve sufficiently large ranges so that this does not happen.","pos":[20096,20170]},{"content":"Managing Dependencies Between .RC, .CPP, and .H Files","pos":[20179,20232]},{"content":"When Visual C++ saves an .RC file, it also saves symbol changes to the corresponding RESOURCE.H file.","pos":[20241,20342]},{"content":"Any of your .CPP files that refer to resources in the .RC file must #include the RESOURCE.H file, usually from within your project's master header file.","pos":[20343,20495]},{"content":"This leads to an undesirable side-effect because of the development environment's internal project management which scans source files for header dependencies.","pos":[20496,20655]},{"content":"Every time you add a new symbol in Visual C++, all the .CPP file that